{"expireTime":9007200844371166000,"key":"transformer-remark-markdown-html-55b6cce1448c22e4b7dd9a162f854478-gatsby-remark-imagesgatsby-remark-responsive-iframegatsby-remark-prismjsgatsby-remark-copy-linked-filesgatsby-remark-smartypants-","val":"<p>Sorry F. Scott Fitzgerald, but The Great Gatsby now belongs to the JavaScript framework. I’m a big fan of this framework and I’ve used it to create both this blog and my personal portfolio site. But what exactly is it?</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 590px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/0a59c85616c6848503a5cbeee8c0a678/be796/leo-gatsby.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 56.08108108108109%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"leo-gatsby\"\n        title=\"leo-gatsby\"\n        src=\"/static/0a59c85616c6848503a5cbeee8c0a678/1c72d/leo-gatsby.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/0a59c85616c6848503a5cbeee8c0a678/a80bd/leo-gatsby.jpg 148w,\n/static/0a59c85616c6848503a5cbeee8c0a678/1c91a/leo-gatsby.jpg 295w,\n/static/0a59c85616c6848503a5cbeee8c0a678/1c72d/leo-gatsby.jpg 590w,\n/static/0a59c85616c6848503a5cbeee8c0a678/be796/leo-gatsby.jpg 780w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Gatsby uses a powerful preconfigurator to build a website that uses only static files. It loads pages incredibly fast, it does server-side rendering, code splitting, data prefetching, image loading, asset optimization and more. All included out of the box. You code and develop, Gatsby transforms it.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 590px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/00ff28d6991d0594a6695526b6d5cb1f/6af66/gatsby.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 75%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"gatsby\"\n        title=\"gatsby\"\n        src=\"/static/00ff28d6991d0594a6695526b6d5cb1f/fcda8/gatsby.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/00ff28d6991d0594a6695526b6d5cb1f/12f09/gatsby.png 148w,\n/static/00ff28d6991d0594a6695526b6d5cb1f/e4a3f/gatsby.png 295w,\n/static/00ff28d6991d0594a6695526b6d5cb1f/fcda8/gatsby.png 590w,\n/static/00ff28d6991d0594a6695526b6d5cb1f/6af66/gatsby.png 640w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Okay, but why use Gatsby over other frameworks? Well, the ecosystem is rich and has great docs, including a number of templates and start designs to get you started. The performance is blazing fast, in a way that will surprise you. Finally, it uses GraphQL for its data layer. Using that, you can collect your data from anywhere: JSON, CMS, APIs, whataver, and at build time Gatsby will create an internal GraphQL server and query all data from the same place, in the same way, for your react components.</p>\n<h3>The Downsides</h3>\n<p><img src=\"/42605a5696cac435bbb274d36365630b/sigh.gif\" alt=\"sigh\"></p>\n<p>Yes, there are always downsides in life and this is no exception. While the framework is great, it does require a knowledge of both React and GraphQL. But hey, if you haven’t learned those yet, it’s never too late to start.</p>"}